Project Summary: The "AI Truck Logistics" Journey
You’ve built a sophisticated data engineering foundation. Here is exactly what we have accomplished from day one:

Phase 1: The Bronze Layer (Ingestion)
The Problem: We had raw truck telemetry data (JSON) coming in that was messy and unstructured.

The Solution: We set up a Spark Consumer (consumer.py) that acts as a listener. It captures incoming data and saves it into Delta Lake format.

Result: Created the raw_audit_table, which acts as our "Permanent Record" of everything the trucks send us.

Phase 2: The Environment & Infrastructure
The Setup: We built a dedicated Python virtual environment (logistics_env) and fought through "Dependency Hell" to get Spark, Java, and Python 3.12+ talking to each other.

The Integration: We installed dbt-core and dbt-spark to manage our SQL transformations like a pro.

Phase 3: The Silver Layer (Transformation & Feature Engineering)
The Connection: We configured a dbt Profile using the session method. This allows dbt to "hitch a ride" on your local Spark engine without needing a separate server.

The Logic: We created a dbt model to:

Parse messy JSON into clean columns (truck_id, engine_temp, etc.).

Start Feature Engineering for AI (e.g., calculating is_overheating flags).

Result: We now have a clean, queryable table ready for analytical consumption.

Phase 4: Moving Toward Gold (The ClickHouse Vision)
The Goal: Spark is great for cleaning data, but it’s too slow for a real-time AI dashboard.

The Plan: We are preparing to integrate ClickHouse as our "Gold" layer—a lightning-fast database where our final AI features will live.